"D/O: Note to self: You still need to review Stone Sublimely Self-Righteous. Every black IPA seems to tie back into that seminal anniversary beer from Stone in some way, and such is doubly true for those that stray over the 7% mark. This beer from Uinta, newly arrived in the Southern California market, is no exception, falling very close to the stylistic origin. Dubh does not attempt to pull any punches; it is in the face of the drinker from start to finish, taunting the palate with dark grain, American hops, and astringency, served in aggressive and palate-choking abundance. It is beautiful in its intensity, but hard to finish--wearing out the palate about half-way through the serving. The brewer is kind not to package this in a larger-format bottle. Twelve ounces is plenty of food for thought."
"the best part of this beer is the aftertaste. perhaps it's the marketing (brewed with hemp seed, and a name pronounced ""doobie""), but the aftertaste is distinctly similar to... well.... you get the idea."
"Good beer that I highly recommend if you are looking for a black IPA. Cheers mates."
